\contentsline {added}{Added: \truncate {\Changestruncatewidth }{ A sensible representation of the ENSO-PNA tropospheric teleconnection is important to fully simulate ENSO impacts to North America \citep {bayr2019} and northeast Brazil \citep {hastenrath2006,taschetto2016}. }}{67}{section*.60}%
\contentsline {added}{Added: \truncate {\Changestruncatewidth }{This impact to SESA is due to the subsidence induced by the anomalous Walker circulation which modifies the moisture transport by the SALLJ from the Amazon to SESA \citep {montini2019}.}}{68}{section*.64}%
\contentsline {added}{Added: \truncate {\Changestruncatewidth }{The anomalous descent over equatorial South America is one cause for the drying response seen during El Niño in the Amazon \citep {marengo2012,cai2020}. However, the ENSO-PNA teleconnection to the tropical north Atlantic leads to a decrease in the SLP field, inducing a warming of the SSTs and a delay in the southward migration of the Atlantic ITCZ \citep {andreoli2012seasonal,jimenez2021}. A slighlty weaker effect of the ENSO-PNA on the tropical north Atlantic SLP field seen in the models (Fig \ref {fig:11}) may suggest this pathway is somewhat weaker than observed but determining the relative influence of this pathway is outside the scope of this chapter. }}{69}{section*.66}%
\contentsline {added}{Added: \truncate {\Changestruncatewidth }{Both modelled and observed responses show degrees of non-linearity in various regions. For example, the precipitation response in the Amazon to La Niña in observations and GC3 N96-pi appears to be relatively constant regardless of the strength of the event. Similarly, in UKESM-hist the precipitation anomalies do not show a linearly increasing response to positive ENSO indices in the same region. This evidence suggests that for some regions there are varying degrees of non-linearity of ENSO impacts.}}{70}{section*.67}%
